snippet.textDisplay:
I can't do either of these. "New year's resolutions" are illusory and themes make me forget the goal.

Lucky for me, I make my changes from night to day, usually after reaching the "edge".

eg: If I eat too much cake in a certain week, I don't eat AT ALL for the following MONTHS (undefined amount of time; 'N' months)._

I don't set goals for myself, but rather the "opposite" (I just do/don't do things without thinking).

In a nutshell: it's all a matter of HABIT!

snippet.textDisplay:
In recent years, I've replaced New year's resolutions with new year's goals. Instead of a specific task that's pass or fail, I go for a more flexible objective that can be adjusted. i.e In 2016, my goal was to create and publish something, like a book or a comic. As that year Drew to a close, I was approaching the end of the first draft of a novella, but knew it wouldn't be ready to publish by year's end. So my goal for 2017 became editing and refining until it was ready. At the end of November, I published my first book on Amazon.

This concept sounds even better, so I think I'll add it into my routine.

snippet.textDisplay: Love this video. I’ve been in various, mainly school, situations where we were required to create goals or SMART goals, and I never connected with that. It always seemed so arbitrary. I also don’t get the New Year’s Resolution thing because I think that if one really wants to change something, one wouldn’t wait for a new year to start. I’m realizing I’ve sort of done themes before without thinking of it as such, and it works. Would love to see another video on this topic.
